TY  - JOUR
T1  - A Behavioral Agency Model of Managerial Risk Taking
AU  - Wiseman, Robert M.
AU  - Gomez-Mejia, Luis R.
Y1  - 1998/01/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.192967
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1998.192967
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 133
EP  - 153
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Building on agency and prospect theory views, we construct, in this article, a behavioral agency model of executive risk taking. In the model we combine elements of internal corporate governance with problem framing to explain executive risk-taking behavior. The model suggests that executive risk taking varies across and within different forms of monitoring and that agents may exhibit risk-seeking as well as risk-averse behaviors. We develop specific propositions that combine monitoring with performance and the framing of strategic problems to explain executive choices of strategic risk. The resulting propositions enhance and extend the agency-based corporate governance literature on executive risk taking.
AB  - Building on agency and prospect theory views, we construct, in this article, a behavioral agency model of executive risk taking. In the model we combine elements of internal corporate governance with problem framing to explain executive risk-taking behavior. The model suggests that executive risk taking varies across and within different forms of monitoring and that agents may exhibit risk-seeking as well as risk-averse behaviors. We develop specific propositions that combine monitoring with performance and the framing of strategic problems to explain executive choices of strategic risk. The resulting propositions enhance and extend the agency-based corporate governance literature on executive risk taking.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.192967
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1998.192967
Y2  - 2026/04/24
