TY  - JOUR
T1  - Objections to an Objectivist Approach to Integrity
AU  - Barry, Bruce
AU  - Stephens, Carroll U.
Y1  - 1998/01/01
PY  - 1998
DA  - 1998/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.192971
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1998.192971
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 162
EP  - 169
VL  - 23
IS  - 1
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This article challenges Becker's objectivist account of integrity in organizations. Although existing approaches to workplace integrity are flawed by conceptual and methodological inconsistencies, an objectivist analysis is unable to resolve these problems and raises new concerns. We develop three lines of argument. First, we critique objectivism as a philosophical system of questionable legitimacy and coherence. Second, we argue that the fundamental objectivist principle of rational egoism is inferior to existing theories of business ethics as a means of defining moral behavior in organizations. Third, we contend that the objectivist account of integrity understates the role of social power as a determinant of organizational choices and outcomes.
AB  - This article challenges Becker's objectivist account of integrity in organizations. Although existing approaches to workplace integrity are flawed by conceptual and methodological inconsistencies, an objectivist analysis is unable to resolve these problems and raises new concerns. We develop three lines of argument. First, we critique objectivism as a philosophical system of questionable legitimacy and coherence. Second, we argue that the fundamental objectivist principle of rational egoism is inferior to existing theories of business ethics as a means of defining moral behavior in organizations. Third, we contend that the objectivist account of integrity understates the role of social power as a determinant of organizational choices and outcomes.
SN  - 0363-7425
M3  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1998.192971
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/amr.1998.192971
Y2  - 2026/04/24
